            those tables live. NFPA 110 is cited and linked only, never reproduced.
2026-07-15  source STILL wip, but the primary is FOUND and it is strong: ASCO Group 5 Controller
            User's Guide, 381333-126K (4000/7000 Series). It publishes both the sequence and its own
            stated verdict on it, which is the WP75 pairing. The load bearing sentence, read directly
            out of the PDF (p.4-4): "Three criteria must be met for the sources to be considered
            in-sync. The phase difference between the sources must be less than 5 degrees, the
            frequency difference must be less than 0.2 Hz, and the voltage difference must be less
            than 5%." Plus a full timer table with defaults AND ranges (p.2-4/2-5), all three
            transition types, and the voltage/frequency table (p.2-2). Russelectric Model 2000 traced
            as an independent cross check: structure agrees, NUMBERS DIFFER (engine start override
            3 sec vs ASCO 1 sec). So the sim names the vendor whose sequence it runs; there is no
            such thing as "the" ATS defaults.
            ⚠ WHY STILL wip, ONE REASON: the copy read is a DISTRIBUTOR'S MIRROR (Rev K), not ASCO's
            own page, which was located but never fetched. Defaults are exactly what this project
            verifies against, and a different revision could carry different ones. 02 proved this
            session that a third party rehost is fine for LOCATING a document and is not evidence
            about its CONTENTS. Fetch 381333-126K from the manufacturer and diff before shipping.
            Found in the primary and left unresolved on purpose: the manual CONTRADICTS ITSELF on the
            Shed Load timer (table p.2-6 says 1.5 sec, narrative p.2-7 says "3 second default"). Do
            not build against it without surfacing the discrepancy.
            Do NOT use any Eaton ATC-300+ number: 4 fetch attempts failed, values came only from a
            search engine's synthesis. Eaton is the vendor that actually uses the TDNE/TDES/TDEN
            names, so the trap is labelling ASCO's traced numbers with Eaton's acronyms. That pairing
            would be fabricated. Use ASCO's own feature names (1C, 2B, 2E, 3A) and cite ASCO.
